title CVerify — Hiring Requirement Artifact Generation

skinparam responseMessageBelowArrow true
skinparam maxMessageSize 300

actor       "Organization Member\n(HR / REPRESENTATIVE / OWNER)" as HR
participant "Next.js Client"                     as C
participant "HiringRequirementController"        as HC
participant "HiringRequirementService"           as SVC
participant "HmacSignatureService"               as HMAC
participant "CVerify.AI\nanalysis_router"        as AI
participant "RequirementArtifactsOrchestrator"   as ORCH
participant "Anthropic Claude"                   as CLAUDE
database    "PostgreSQL"                         as DB
database    "Redis"                              as R

== Trigger (generate everything) ==
HR -> C  : "Generate artifacts"
C  -> HC : POST /api/v1/hiring-requirements/{id}/generate-artifacts
HC -> SVC : GetByIdAsync(id)
alt not found
    HC --> C : 404
end
HC -> HC : _ = Task.Run(scoped GenerateArtifactsAsync(id, userId))
HC --> C : 202 Accepted { jobId = id, status = "Generating" }

note right of HC #ffdddd
  Generation runs on a **detached `Task.Run` with a fresh DI scope and
  `CancellationToken.None`** — it is not routed through any
  IHostedService or queue. Nothing tracks it across a process restart;
  the only record is the AiStreamingSession row moving to Running.
  `jobId` returned to the client is just the requirement id.
end note

SVC -> DB : requirement status -> Generating
SVC -> DB : CreateSessionAsync(id, "jd-generation", model "Claude 3.5 Sonnet", provider "Anthropic")
SVC -> DB : UpdateSessionStatusAsync(id, "Running")
SVC -> HMAC : CreateSignatureHeaders("POST",\n"/api/v1/hiring-requirements/generate/stream", body)
HMAC --> SVC : HMACSHA256(METHOD + URL + BODY + TIMESTAMP + NONCE, SharedSecret)
SVC -> AI  : POST /api/v1/hiring-requirements/generate/stream\nX-Client-Id: cverify-core, X-Timestamp, X-Nonce,\nX-Correlation-Id = requirementId, X-Signature\n(ResponseHeadersRead)

== AI service: one Claude call, five artifacts ==
AI -> ORCH : generate_all_artifacts_async(requirement_data, correlation_id)
ORCH --> SVC : data: {Running, GenerateUnifiedRequirements, 10%}

group _call_claude_with_validation (max_retries = 2)
    ORCH -> CLAUDE : system + get_unified_requirements_prompt(requirement_data)\nstream=True, max_tokens=8192
    CLAUDE --> ORCH : raw text
    ORCH -> ORCH : _repair_and_extract_json (json_repair fallback)
    ORCH -> ORCH : UnifiedRequirementArtifactsResponse(**parsed)
    alt Pydantic validation fails
        ORCH -> CLAUDE : re-prompt with the validation error appended\n("Your previous response failed validation with: ...")
        note right of ORCH
          Self-correction is capped at 2 retries; the third failure raises
          "Failed to generate valid artifact schema after 2 correction attempts".
        end note
    end
end

note over ORCH
  **A single Claude response produces all five artifacts.** They are not
  five model calls — the orchestrator slices one validated Pydantic object
  and fans it out as five successive SSE events.
end note

ORCH --> SVC : data: {GenerateJobDescription, 40%, artifactType "JobDescription", jsonData}
ORCH --> SVC : data: {GenerateEvaluationRubric, 60%, artifactType "EvaluationRubric", jsonData}
ORCH --> SVC : data: {GenerateInterviewBlueprint, 80%, artifactType "InterviewBlueprint", jsonData}
ORCH --> SVC : data: {GenerateJobPostMetadata, 90%, artifactType "JobPostMetadata", jsonData}
ORCH --> SVC : data: {GenerateCandidateDiscoveryProfile, 95%, artifactType "CandidateDiscoveryProfile", jsonData}
ORCH --> SVC : data: {Completed, 100%}

loop for each streamed event
    SVC -> DB : UpdateSessionProgressAsync / UpsertStageAsync / AddLogAsync
    SVC -> DB : AddMetricAsync input_tokens / output_tokens / cost_usd
    SVC -> DB : SaveArtifactAsync(requirementId, artifactType, jsonData)\n-> RequirementArtifact | EvaluationRubric | InterviewBlueprint
    SVC -> R  : PUBLISH hiring requirement progress
end
SVC -> DB : requirement status -> Generated; session -> Completed
alt any exception
    SVC -> DB : requirement status -> Failed
    SVC -> DB : UpdateSessionStatusAsync(id, "Failed", errorMessage)
end

== Regenerate one artifact (POST {id}/artifacts/generate) ==
C  -> HC : POST /api/v1/hiring-requirements/{id}/artifacts/generate { artifactType }
HC -> SVC : GenerateArtifactAsync(id, artifactType, userId)
SVC -> HMAC : CreateSignatureHeaders("POST",\n"/api/v1/hiring-requirements/generate-artifact/stream", body)
SVC -> AI  : POST /api/v1/hiring-requirements/generate-artifact/stream\n{ ..., artifactType }
AI -> ORCH : generate_artifact_stream(requirement_data, artifact_type, ...)

note over ORCH #ffdddd
  **BUG — GROUND-TRUTH §6.2: `generate_artifact_stream` ignores its
  `artifact_type` argument.** The whole body of the function is:

      async for progress in self.generate_all_artifacts_async(...):
          yield progress

  (orchestrator.py:67-76, comment "Regenerate all artifacts together
  to ensure data consistency"). Consequences:
  * asking to regenerate only the InterviewBlueprint silently rewrites
    the JobDescription, EvaluationRubric, JobPostMetadata and
    CandidateDiscoveryProfile as well — any manual edits are lost;
  * cost and latency of a "single artifact" request equal a full run;
  * the .NET caller still believes it requested one type, and its
    cancel/status bookkeeping (`RequirementArtifacts` row for that
    artifactType) reflects only one of the five writes.
end note

ORCH --> SVC : five artifactType events again (identical to the full run)
SVC -> DB   : SaveArtifactAsync x5

== Progress stream & publish ==
C  -> HC : GET /api/v1/hiring-requirements/{id}/progress-stream   (text/event-stream)
HC -> R  : SUBSCRIBE requirement progress channel
R  --> HC : live events
HC --> C : data: <event> … data: [DONE]

HR -> C  : "Publish"
C  -> HC : POST /api/v1/hiring-requirements/{id}/publish
HC -> SVC : PublishAsync(id)
SVC -> DB : INSERT RequirementSnapshot + ArtifactSnapshots\n(a JobDescription snapshot is synthesised if absent)
HC --> C : 200 { snapshotId, version, publishedAt }

note right of SVC
  The snapshot is what downstream matching reads
  (`JobVacancy.RequirementSnapshot.CapabilitiesJson`), so publishing
  freezes the artifact set at that moment — a later silent
  regenerate-all does **not** retroactively change a published snapshot.
end note

@enduml
